# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ncurses-tui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] The name is a pun on the term "cursor optimization".
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] It is a library of functions that manage an application's display on character-cell terminals (e.g., VT100).
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] ncurses is the approved replacement for 4.4BSD classic curses.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Using curses, programmers are able to write text-based applications without writing directly for any specific terminal type.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] The curses library on the executing system sends the correct control characters based on the terminal type.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] It provides an abstraction of one or more windows that maps onto the terminal screen.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Each window is represented by a character matrix.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] The programmer sets up the desired appearance of each window, then tells the curses package to update the screen.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] The library determines a minimal set of changes that are needed to update the display and then executes these using the terminal's specific capabilities and control sequences.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] In short, this means that the programmer creates a character matrix of how the screen should look and lets curses handle the work.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] The curses API is described in several places.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Most implementations of curses use a database that can describe the capabilities of thousands of different terminals.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] There are a few implementations, such as PDCurses, which use specialized device drivers rather than a terminal database.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Most implementations use terminfo; some use termcap.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Curses has the advantage of back-portability to character-cell terminals and simplicity.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] For an application that does not require bit-mapped graphics or multiple fonts, an interface implementation using curses will usually be much simpler and faster than one using an X toolkit.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] The first curses library was written by Ken Arnold and originally released with BSD UNIX, where it was used for several games, most notably *Rogue*.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Some improvements were made to the BSD library in the 1990s as "4.4BSD" curses, e.g., to provide more than one type of video highlighting.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] The name "curses" is a pun on *cursor optimization*.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Sometimes it is incorrectly stated that curses was used by the vi editor; in actuality, the code in curses that optimizes moving the cursor was borrowed from vi, which predated curses.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] According to Goodheart, Ken Arnold's original implementation of curses started by reusing functions from the termcap library, and adding to that.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] A few years later, Mary Ann Horton, who had maintained the vi and termcap sources at Berkeley, went to AT&T Corporation and made a different version using terminfo, which became part of UNIX System III and UNIX System V.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Due to licensing restrictions on the latter, the BSD and AT&T versions of the library were developed independently.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] The BSD version gave little support here.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] This was not supported in the BSD version.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] AT&T curses development appears to have halted in the mid-1990s when X/Open Curses was defined.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] In 1995, BSD maintainer, Keith Bostic, officially deprecated the curses library in favor of ncurses.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Development of ncurses and PDCurses continues.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] A version of BSD curses continues to be maintained in the NetBSD operating system (wide character support, termcap to terminfo migration, etc.).
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Although the ncurses library was initially developed under Linux, OpenBSD, FreeBSD, and NetBSD, it has been ported to many other ANSI/POSIX UNIX systems, mainly by Thomas Dickey.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] PDCurses, while not identical to ncurses, uses the same function calls and operates the same way as ncurses does except that PDCurses targets different devices, e.g., console windows for DOS, Win32, OS/2, as well as X11.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Porting between the two is not difficult.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] For example, the roguelike game *ADOM* was written for Linux and ncurses, later ported to DOS and PDCurses.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Curses is designed to facilitate GUI-like functionality on a text-only device, such as a PC running in console mode, a hardware ANSI terminal, a Telnet or SSH client, or similar.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Curses-based software is software whose user interface is implemented through the curses library, or a compatible library (such as ncurses).
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Curses-based programs often have a user interface that resembles a traditional graphical user interface, including 'widgets' such as text boxes and scrollable lists, rather than the command line interface (CLI) most commonly found on text-only devices.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] This can make them more user-friendly than a CLI-based program, while still being able to run on text-only devices.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Curses-based software can also have a lighter resource footprint and operate on a wider range of systems (both in terms of hardware and software) than their GUI-based counterparts.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] This includes old pre-1990 machines along with modern embedded systems using text-only displays.
[src:ncurses-tui/curses-programming-library] Curses is most commonly associated with Unix-like operating systems, although implementations for Microsoft Windows also exist.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] In a graphical user interface (GUI), a **graphical widget** (also **graphical control element** or **control**) is an element of interaction, such as a button or a scroll bar.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Controls are software components that a computer user interacts with through direct manipulation to read or edit information about an application.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] User interface libraries such as Windows Presentation Foundation, Qt, GTK, and Cocoa, contain a collection of controls and the logic to render these.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Each widget facilitates a specific type of user-computer interaction, and appears as a visible part of the application's GUI as defined by the theme and rendered by the rendering engine.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] The theme makes all widgets adhere to a unified aesthetic design and creates a sense of overall cohesion.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Some widgets support interaction with the user, for example labels, buttons, and check boxes.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Others act as containers that group the widgets added to them, for example windows, panels, and tabs.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Structuring a user interface with widget toolkits allows developers to reuse code for similar tasks, and provides users with a common language for interaction, maintaining consistency throughout the whole information system.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Graphical user interface builders facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] They automatically generate all the source code for a widget from general descriptions provided by the developer, usually through direct manipulation.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Around 1920, *widget* entered American English, as a generic term for any useful device, particularly a product manufactured for sale; a gadget.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] In 1988, the term *widget* is attested in the context of Project Athena and the X Window System.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] The same year, in the manual *X Toolkit Widgets - C Language X Interface* by Ralph R.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Finally, still in the same year, Ralph R.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Any widget displays an information arrangement changeable by the user, such as a window or a text box.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] The defining characteristic of a widget is to provide a single interaction point for the direct manipulation of a given kind of data.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] In other words, widgets are basic visual building blocks which, combined in an application, hold all the data processed by the application and the available interactions on this data.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are graphical elements used to build the human-machine-interface of a program.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are implemented like software components.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Widget toolkits and software frameworks, like e.g.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] GTK+ or Qt, contain them in software libraries so that programmers can use them to build GUIs for their programs.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] A family of common reusable widgets has evolved for holding general information based on the Palo Alto Research Center Inc. research for the Xerox Alto User Interface.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Various implementations of these generic widgets are often packaged together in widget toolkits, which programmers use to build graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Most operating systems include a set of ready-to-tailor widgets that a programmer can incorporate in an application, specifying how it is to behave.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Each type of widget generally is defined as a class by object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Therefore, many widgets are derived from class inheritance.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] In the context of an application, a widget may be *enabled* or *disabled* at a given point in time.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] An enabled widget has the capacity to respond to events, such as keystrokes or mouse actions.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] A widget that cannot respond to such events is considered disabled.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] The appearance of a widget typically differs depending on whether it is enabled or disabled; when disabled, a widget may be drawn in a lighter color ("**grayed out**") or be obscured visually in some way.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] On pop-up dialogues, buttons might appear greyed out shortly after appearance to prevent accidental clicking or inadvertent double-tapping.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] Widgets are sometimes qualified as *virtual* to distinguish them from their physical counterparts, e.g.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] *virtual* buttons that can be clicked with a pointer, vs. physical buttons that can be pressed with a finger (such as those on a computer mouse).
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] A related (but different) concept is the desktop widget, a small specialized GUI application that provides some visual information and/or easy access to frequently used functions such as clocks, calendars, news aggregators, calculators and desktop notes.
[src:ncurses-tui/graphical-widget] These kinds of widgets are hosted by a widget engine.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] ncurses is a free and open-source software emulation of curses from System V Release 4.0 (SVr4).
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] There are bindings for ncurses in a variety of programming languages, including Ada, Common Lisp, Python, Gambas, Ruby, PHP, JavaScript, Perl, Object REXX (ooRexx) and Rust.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] As the new version, ncurses is a free and open-source software emulation of the System V Release 4.0 (SVr4) curses, which was an enhancement over the discontinued 4.4 BSD curses.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] The XSI Curses standard issued by X/Open is explicitly and closely modeled on UNIX System V.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] The first curses library was developed at University of California, Berkeley, for a BSD operating system, around 1980 to support Rogue, a text-based adventure game.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] It originally used the termcap library, which was used in other programs, such as the vi editor.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] The success of the BSD curses library prompted Bell Labs to release an enhanced curses library in their System V Release 2 Unix systems.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] This library was more powerful and instead of using termcap, it used terminfo.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] However, due to AT&T's policy regarding the distribution of source code, the improved curses library was not widely adopted in the BSD community.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Around 1982, Pavel Curtis started work on a freeware clone of the Bell Labs curses, named **pcurses**, which was maintained by various people through 1986.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] The pcurses library was further improved when Zeyd Ben-Halim took over the development effort in late 1991.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] The new library was released as ncurses in November 1993, with version 1.8.1 as the first major release.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Subsequent work, through version 1.8.8 (M1995), was driven by Eric S.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Raymond, who added the form and menu libraries written by Juergen Pfeifer.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Since 1996, it has been maintained by Thomas E.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Most ncurses calls can be easily ported to the old curses.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] System V curses implementations can support BSD curses programs with just a recompilation.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] However, a few areas are problematic, such as handling terminal resizing, since no counterpart exists in the old curses.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] ncurses can use either terminfo (with extensible data) or termcap.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Other implementations of curses generally use terminfo; a minority use termcap.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Few (mytinfo was an older exception) use both.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] ncurses is a part of the GNU Project, but is not distributed under the GNU General Public License (GPL) or GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL).
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Instead, it is distributed under a permissive free software licence: the MIT License.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] This is due to the agreement made with the Free Software Foundation at the time the developers assigned their copyright.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Dickey, this precludes relicensing to the GPL in any version, since it would place restrictions on the programs that will be able to link to the libraries.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Some, such as GNU Screen and w3m, use only the termcap interface and perform screen management themselves.
[src:ncurses-tui/ncurses] Others, such as GNU Midnight Commander and Yet another Setup Tool (YaST), use the curses programming interface.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] A **terminal emulator**, or **terminal application**, is a computer program that emulates a video terminal within another display architecture.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Though typically synonymous with a shell or text terminal, the term *terminal* covers all remote terminals, including graphical interfaces.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] A terminal emulator inside a graphical user interface is often called a **terminal window**.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] A terminal window allows the user access to a text terminal and all its applications such as command-line interfaces (CLI) and text user interface (TUI) applications.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] These may be running either on the same machine or on a different one via telnet, ssh, dial-up, or over a direct serial connection.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] On Unix-like operating systems, it is common to have one or more terminal windows connected to the local machine.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Terminals usually support a set of escape sequences for controlling color, cursor position, etc.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Examples include the family of terminal control sequence standards that includes ECMA-48, ANSI X3.64, and ISO/IEC 6429.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] In the early days of computing, with the advent of interactive computing, the prevailing model involved a central computer connected to multiple terminals.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] This configuration, known as the centralized or mainframe model, featured a powerful central computer that performed all the processing tasks, while terminals served as input/output devices for users to interact with the system.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] These systems were initially character based.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] A character-oriented terminal is a type of computer terminal that communicates with its host one character at a time, as opposed to a block-oriented terminal that communicates in blocks of data.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] It is the most common type of data terminal, because it is easy to implement and program.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Connection to the mainframe computer or terminal server is achieved via RS-232 serial links, Ethernet or other proprietary protocols.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Character-oriented terminals can be "dumb" or "smart".
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Dumb terminals are those that can interpret a limited number of control codes (CR, LF, etc.) but do not have the ability to process special escape sequences that perform functions such as clearing a line, clearing the screen, or controlling cursor position.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] In this context dumb terminals are sometimes dubbed *glass Teletypes*, for they essentially have the same limited functionality as does a mechanical Teletype.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] This type of dumb terminal is still supported on modern Unix-like systems by setting the environment variable `TERM` to `dumb`.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Smart or intelligent terminals are those that also have the ability to process escape sequences, in particular the VT52, VT100 or ANSI escape sequences.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] When personal computers became ubiquitous in the 1980s, they offered the option of running software on the user's personal computer, providing an opportunity to replace the expensive and space consuming hardware terminals with something that had additional functions.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Immediately software became available, that could emulate the functions of the hardware terminals on a PC.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Examples of such software for DOS were Telix or Telemate, which was published in 1988 and could emulate a DEC VT102 terminal.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Workstations, usually running versions of Unix, also became common in the 1980s.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Unix systems usually provided access to the command line with locally-attached or dial-up terminals.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Unix workstations were designed to be used primarily through a graphical user interface (GUI); to provide access to the command line, the GUI included terminal emulator applications that behaved like locally-attached terminals.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Through the success of Linux on servers, especially running on data centers and cloud servers, the necessity of accessing remote computers through character-based terminal emulators remains.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators, such as xterm, implement additional features not present in the emulated terminal.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Additionally, programs have been developed to emulate assorted system console "terminals" such as the Sun workstation console and the Linux console.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Finally, some emulators simply refer to a set of standards, such as the standards for ANSI escape codes.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Such programs are available on many platforms, including DOS, Unix-like systems including Linux and macOS, Windows, and embedded operating systems found in cellphones and industrial hardware.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] In the past, Unix and Unix-like systems used serial port devices such as RS-232 ports, and provided `/dev/*` device files for them.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] With terminal emulators these device files are themselves emulated by a pair of pseudoterminal devices.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] These in turn emulate a physical port/connection to the host computing endpoint – hardware provided by operating system APIs, or software such as rlogin, telnet or SSH, among others.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] In Linux systems, for example, these would be `/dev/ptyp0` (for the master side) and `/dev/ttyp0` (for the slave side) pseudoterminal devices respectively.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] There are also special virtual console files like `/dev/console`.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] In text mode, writing to the file displays text on the virtual console and reading from the file returns text the user writes to the virtual console.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] As with other text terminals, there are also special escape sequences, control characters and functions that a program can use, most easily via a library such as *ncurses*.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] For more complex operations, the programs can use console and terminal special *ioctl* system calls.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] One can compare devices using the patterns vcs ("virtual console screen") and vcsa ("virtual console screen with attributes") such as `/dev/vcs1` and `/dev/vcsa1`.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators also include escape sequences for configuring the behavior of the terminal to facilitate good interoperation between the terminal and programs running inside of it, for example to configure paste bracketing.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] The virtual consoles can be configured in the file `/etc/inittab` read by *init*—typically it starts the text mode login process *getty* for several virtual consoles.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] X Window System can be configured in `/etc/inittab` or by an X display manager.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] A number of Linux distributions use systemd instead of init, which also allows virtual console configuration.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement a local echo function, which may erroneously be named "half-duplex", or still slightly incorrectly "echoplex" (which is formally an error detection mechanism rather than an input display option).
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement local editing, also known as "line-at-a-time mode".
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] This is also mistakenly referred to as "half-duplex".
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] In this mode, the terminal emulator only sends complete lines of input to the host system.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] The user enters and edits a line, but it is held locally within the terminal emulator as it is being edited.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] It is not transmitted until the user signals its completion, usually with the ↵ Enter key on the keyboard or a "send" button of some sort in the user interface.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] At that point, the entire line is transmitted.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Line-at-a-time mode implies local echo, since otherwise the user will not be able to see the line as it is being edited and constructed.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] However, line-at-a-time mode is independent of echo mode and does not *require* local echo.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] When entering a password, for example, line-at-a-time entry with local editing is possible, but local echo is turned off (otherwise the password would be displayed).
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] The complexities of line-at-a-time mode are exemplified by the line-at-a-time mode option in the telnet protocol.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] To implement it correctly, the *Network Virtual Terminal* implementation provided by the terminal emulator program must be capable of recognizing and properly dealing with "interrupt" and "abort" events that arrive in the middle of locally editing a line.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] In asynchronous terminals data can flow in any direction at any time.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] In **synchronous terminals** a protocol controls who may send data when.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] IBM 3270-based terminals used with IBM mainframe computers are an example of **synchronous terminals**.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] They operate in an essentially "screen-at-a-time" mode (also known as block mode).
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Users can make numerous changes to a page, before submitting the updated screen to the remote machine as a single action.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators that simulate the 3270 protocol are available for most operating systems, for use both by those administering systems such as the z9, as well as those using the corresponding applications such as CICS.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Other examples of synchronous terminals include the IBM 5250, ICL 7561, Honeywell Bull VIP7800 and Hewlett-Packard 700/92.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles, also called virtual terminals, are emulated text terminals, using the keyboard and monitor of a personal computer or workstation.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] The word "text" is key since virtual consoles are not GUI terminals and they do not run inside a graphical interface.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles are found on most Unix-like systems.
[src:ncurses-tui/terminal-emulator] They are primarily used to access and interact with servers, without using a graphical desktop environment.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Like modern GUIs, they can use the entire screen area and may accept mouse and other inputs.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] They may also use color and often structure the display using box-drawing characters such as ┌ and ╣.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The modern context of use is usually a terminal emulator.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] In the early years of computing, text terminals were usually keyboard/printer devices.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Currently, however, keyboard/display devices dominate.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Examples are TN3270, xterm for X Window System and win32 console (in a window mode) for Microsoft Windows.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] This usually supports programs that expect a real text mode display, but may run considerably slower.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Certain functions of an advanced text mode, such as an own font uploading, almost certainly become unavailable.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The communication capabilities usually become reduced to a serial line or its emulation, possibly with few ioctl()s as an out-of-band channel in such cases as Telnet and Secure Shell.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] This is the worst case, because software restrictions hinder the use of capabilities of a remote display device.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] From text application's point of view, the display type is determined by the API, e.g., curses, TPUT.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Under Linux and other Unix-like systems, a program easily accommodates to any of the three cases because the same interface (namely, standard streams) controls the display and keyboard.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Many TUI programming libraries are available to help developers build TUI applications.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] American National Standards Institute (ANSI) standard ANSI X3.64 defines a standard set of escape sequences that can be used to drive terminals to create TUIs (see ANSI escape code).
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Escape sequences may be supported for all three cases mentioned in the above section, allowing arbitrary cursor movements and color changes.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] However, not all terminals follow this standard, and many non-compatible but functionally equivalent sequences exist.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] On IBM PC compatibles, the Basic Input Output System (BIOS) and MS-DOS system calls provide a way to write text on the screen, and the ANSI.SYS driver could process standard ANSI escape sequences.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] However, programmers soon learned that writing data directly to the screen buffer was far faster and simpler to program, and less error-prone; see VGA-compatible text mode for details.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] This change in programming methods resulted in many DOS TUI programs.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The Windows console environment is notorious for its emulation of certain EGA/VGA text mode features, particularly random access to the text buffer, even if the application runs in a window.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] On the other hand, programs running under Windows (both native and DOS applications) have much less control of the display and keyboard than Linux and DOS programs can have, because of aforementioned Windows console layer.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Most often those programs used a blue background for the main screen, with white or yellow characters, although commonly they had also user color customization.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] They often used box-drawing characters in IBM's code page 437.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Later, the interface became deeply influenced by graphical user interfaces (GUI), adding pull-down menus, overlapping windows, dialog boxes and GUI widgets operated by mnemonics or keyboard shortcuts.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Soon mouse input was added – either at text resolution as a simple colored box or at graphical resolution thanks to the ability of the Enhanced Graphics Adapter (EGA) and Video Graphics Array (VGA) display adapters to redefine the text character shapes by software – providing additional functions.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Some notable programs of this kind were Microsoft Word, DOS Shell, WordPerfect, Norton Commander, Turbo Vision based Borland Turbo Pascal and Turbo C (the latter included the conio library), Lotus 1-2-3 and many others.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Some of these interfaces survived even during the Microsoft Windows 3.1x period in the early 1990s.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] For example, the Microsoft C 6.0 compiler, used to write true GUI programs under 16-bit Windows, still has its own TUI.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Since its start, Microsoft Windows includes a console to display DOS software.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Later versions added the Windows console as a native interface for command-line interface and TUI programs.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The console usually opens in window mode, but it can be switched to full, true text mode screen and vice versa by pressing the Alt and Enter keys together.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Full-screen mode is not available in Windows Vista and later, but may be used with some workarounds.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Windows Terminal is a multi-tabbed terminal emulator that Microsoft has developed for Windows 10 and later as a replacement for Windows Console.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The Windows Subsystem for Linux which was added to Windows by Microsoft in 2019, supports running Linux text-based apps on Windows, within Windows console, Windows Terminal, and other Windows-based terminals.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] In Unix-like operating systems, TUIs are often constructed using the terminal control library *curses*, or *ncurses* (a mostly compatible library), or the alternative *S-Lang* library.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The advent of the *curses* library with Berkeley Unix created a portable and stable API for which to write TUIs.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The ability to talk to various text terminal types using the same interfaces led to more widespread use of "visual" Unix programs, which occupied the entire terminal screen instead of using a simple line interface.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] This can be seen in text editors such as vi, mail clients such as pine or mutt, system management tools such as SMIT, SAM, FreeBSD's Sysinstall and web browsers such as lynx.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Some applications, such as w3m, and older versions of pine and vi use the less-able termcap library, performing many of the functions associated with curses within the application.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Custom TUI applications based on *widgets* can be easily developed using the dialog program (based on ncurses), or the Whiptail program (based on S-Lang).
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] In addition, the rise in popularity of Linux brought many former DOS users to a Unix-like platform, which has fostered a DOS influence in many TUIs.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The program minicom, for example, is modeled after the popular DOS program Telix.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Some other TUI programs, such as the Twin desktop, were ported over.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Most Unix-like operating systems (Linux, FreeBSD, etc.) support virtual consoles, typically accessed through a Ctrl-Alt-F key combination.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] For example, under Linux up to 64 consoles may be accessed (12 via function keys), each displaying in full-screen text mode.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The free software program GNU Screen provides for managing multiple sessions inside a single TUI, and so can be thought of as being like a window manager for text-mode and command-line interfaces.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The proprietary macOS text editor BBEdit includes a *shell worksheet* function that works as a full-screen shell window.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The free Emacs text editor can run a shell inside of one of its buffers to provide similar functionality.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] There are several shell implementations in Emacs, but only `ansi-term` is suitable for running TUI programs.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The other common shell modes, `shell` and `eshell` only emulate command lines and TUI programs will complain "Terminal is not fully functional" or display a garbled interface.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The free Vim and Neovim text editors have terminal windows (simulating xterm).
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] The feature is intended for running jobs, parallel builds, or tests, but can also be used (with window splits and tab pages) as a lightweight terminal multiplexer.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] VAX/VMS (later known as OpenVMS) had a similar facility to *curses* known as the Screen Management facility or SMG.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] This could be invoked from the command line or called from programs using the SMG$ library.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Another kind of TUI is the primary interface of the Oberon operating system, first released in 1988 and still maintained.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Unlike most other text-based user interfaces, Oberon does not use a text-mode console or terminal, but requires a large bit-mapped display, on which text is the primary target for mouse clicks.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Analogous to a link in hypertext, a command has the format `Module.Procedure *parameters* ~` and is activated with a mouse middle-click.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Text displayed anywhere on the screen can be edited, and if formatted with the required command syntax, can be middle-clicked and executed.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Any text file containing suitably-formatted commands can be used as a so-called **tool text**, thus serving as a user-configurable menu.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Even the output of a previous command can be edited and used as a new command.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] This approach is radically different from both conventional dialogue-oriented console menus or command-line interfaces but bears some similarities to the worksheet interface of the Macintosh Programmer's Workshop.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Since it does not use graphical widgets, only plain text, but offers comparable functionality to a GUI with a tiling window manager, it is referred to as a Text User Interface or TUI.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] For a short introduction, see the 2nd paragraph on page four of the first published *Report on the Oberon System*.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Oberon's UI influenced the design of the Acme text editor and email client for the Plan 9 from Bell Labs operating system.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Modern embedded systems are capable of displaying TUI on a monitor like personal computers.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] This functionality is usually implemented using specialized integrated circuits, modules, or using FPGA.
[src:ncurses-tui/text-based-user-interface] Video circuits or modules are usually controlled using VT100-compatible command set over UART, FPGA designs usually allow direct video memory access.
